<br>
BTW, the terrorist loving wackos over at <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.indymedia.org">Indymedia.batshit</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> have declared White a &quot;war criminal&quot; for this and similar writings. (so much for their bleatings about free speech and their denials of authoritarian intent).<br>
 <br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  &quot;Imagine a boot and a sandal stamping on a human face-forever&quot;<br>
(apologies to George Orwell)<br>
<br>
<br>
A Clash of... Something?<br>
<br>
<br>
I have noticed, along with other bloggers, that over these last few months, a seismic movement in world politics - a grand realignment, a &quot;shifting of tectonic plates&quot;, as one of them put it- seems to be occurring. Surfing the Internet, reading books and magazines, and just generally trying to keep up with what's going on, gives me the feeling that there are vast and significant changes occurring in the world, to which the mainstream news media seem oblivious. When President Bush said &quot;you are either with us or against us&quot; in the war against terrorism, he was actually outlining where the main fracture line really is, and the realignment of politics that will define the great conflict of the 21st Century.<br>
<br>
<br>
The Shape of Wars to Come<br>
<br>
<br>
What, you may ask, am I talking about? Well, there's the assassination of a &quot;right-wing&quot; Dutch politician by an animal-rights activist, the al-Aqsa war against Israel and the September 11 attack on the United States, along with the explosion of anti-Semitism in Europe, and the ongoing US campaign against international terrorism. All these straws in the wind seem to be connected, to be bringing about a fundamental change in the world political scene that will match the Cold War in scope and duration. It's not just me, either- a number of bloggers and also writers such as Victor Davis Hanson have sensed it too.<br>
<br>
<br>
The one who has perceived this most clearly was Professor Samuel Huntingdon. In his article of a few years ago, &quot;A Clash of Civilizations&quot;, he saw that the great conflict of the 21st century would be along civilizational lines- &quot;the West vs. the Rest&quot;, as one commentator put it, or at least the West vs. Islam. I agree, but only up to a point. <br>
<br>
<br>
I do agree that the 21st Century will indeed be dominated by a vast conflict that will manifest itself in many ways on many different battlefields. It will be like the cold war in some ways, with guerillas, terrorists, great clashes of ideologies and large-scale conventional wars against terrorist sponsoring states. It will be completely different in others, for although there will be no one state or leader aiding and controlling the terrorists and guerillas, there will be lots of non-state organizations operating independently, with assassinations and bombings. (One recent article in the National Review urged us to think of what we will be facing as being more like James Bond vs. SPECTRE than NATO vs. USSR). <br>
<br>
<br>
But it won't just be a &quot;clash of civilizations&quot;, although there will be some elements of this. The fault lines are not just between civilizations, but within them as well. It will be a war between the creative force of civilization and the destroying force of barbarism. <br>
<br>
<br>
The West has its own home-made barbarians (such as peace and anti-globalization activists), who are joining forces with non-Western barbarians such as Islamic fundamentalists, against the civilized of the West and other civilized non-Westerners. It will be a war for civilization and the consequences will be - to say the least - interesting.<br>
<br>
<br>
How Did We Get From There?<br>
<br>
<br>
It began during the the Cold War. This, please remember, wasn't just a struggle between two areas on a map- the Soviet bloc vs. the Free World. It was also an internal split as well, with people taking sides within their own countries, with the various Communist parties in the West, and underground dissident groups in the Soviet Union. It was never more clearly demonstrated than in America during the Vietnam War. <br>
<br>
<br>
The U.S. conduct of that war brought into the mainstream of American life a group, or should I say a loose coalition, of people who were deeply, fundamentally and totally opposed not just to their country's policies but to its' very existence as a state. The &quot;peace movement&quot; included within its' ranks those who sought to destroy their country and everything it stood for, and were prepared to support anyone who was an enemy of the United States. <br>
<br>
<br>
These people have been around for a long time, but only in the 1960s did they begin to aquire major influence over American life. They were the kind of people who created the French and Russian Revolutions, and they are now moving towards allying with the kind of people who created the Iranian Revolution, National Socialism and Fascism. Many are still alive, still full of hate, and just as sympathetic to their country's enemies as ever. (Noam Chomsky is just the best known example).<br>
<br>
<br>
Now that Islamic fundamentalism (also called Islamofascism- another blogger term) has emerged as the new main enemy of the West, the West's Left-wingers are siding with them (to become a &quot;Fifth Column&quot; so to speak, just as they were during the Cold War), and they are co-operating on the age-old principle that &quot;the enemy of my enemy is my friend&quot;. One has only to look at the increasing support being given to the Palestinians by the Left in numerous countries in Europe to see how this is happening.<br>
<br>
<br>
I believe that this is the second stage of a war against Western Civilization itself. The first stage, the initial skirmishing if you like, started in the 1930's with the rise of Communism, National Socialism and the growing anti-Semitism of the Middle East. The first major war between barbarism and civilization occurred when Hitler's National Socialists attempted to cast down the West and replace it with a new form of scientificially-backed barbarism that, fortunately, was defeated. <br>
<br>
<br>
The war against Western Civilization was continued by the Communists and carried on through to the end of the Cold War. During this period, the Soviets and the Americans attempted to mobilize the Muslim world in support of their respective ideologies, with varying levels of success. The end of the Cold War saw the end of Socialism in most areas of the world in which it had previously reigned supreme, but the anti-Western coalition that the Soviets had created via their supporters in the universities, news media and trade unions of the West still remained. <br>
<br>
<br>
Also, within the confines of the Cold War, another anti-Western alliance had begun to emerge. The Arab world ceased to be a Soviet proxy and became an independent force in world politics, fighting both America and Russia, and continuing to do so in places like Afghanistan and Chechnya. The terrorist attacks aimed at Israel were part of this, as Israel was seen as a &quot;lesser Satan&quot; to the U.S. The Gulf War between Iraq and Iran was a struggle over predominance in the Persian Gulf region, but the Second Gulf War- the US-Iraq one- has mutated into another chapter in the civilizational war.<br>
<br>
<br>
War Against the West Number III<br>
<br>
With the attacks on the World Trade Centre and the Pentagon on the 11th of September 2001, the first round of skirmishing came to an end. Since then, we have entered the second stage of the war, with the formation of a new grand anti-Western, anti-American, and, of course, anti-Jewish alliance. However disparate the elements of this may seem, they are part and parcel of the same thing- someone who burns an American flag is just as happy to burn an Israeli one as well. They can cause a great deal of damage, if we do not act swiftly against them. <br>
<br>
<br>
Jackboots and Sandals Marching Side by Side.<br>
<br>
<br>
This alliance is a coming together of two distinct groups which, for convenience sake (and with my tongue firmly in my cheek), I will call the &quot;Jackboots&quot; and the &quot;Sandals&quot;. The &quot;Jackboots&quot; are the extreme right wing National (as opposed to International) socialists, with anti immigrant, anti-Semitic, anti-American racists like Le Pen in France, shading over to Jorg Haider in Austria.<br>
<br>
<br>
The &quot;Sandals&quot; (or, if you like, &quot;Sandalistas&quot;, as conservative writer P. J. O'Rourke called them) include feminists, gay activists (not to be confused with ordinary gays), Greens, animal righters, Palestinian worshippers, Cold War Left-overs like Fidel Castro, and academics like Edward Said and Noam Chomsky. I include here the Islamo-fascist anti-Semites of the Middle East, as well as those Muslims elsewhere who have joined the anti-West alliance.<br>
<br>
<br>
While it might seem at first glance that they have nothing in common, I think that recent events in France have demonstrated just the opposite, as I will explain. <br>
<br>
<br>
When America's war against terrorism was joined by Israel's anti-terrorist war in the West Bank and Gaza, it gave the anti-Semites and anti-Americans a new flag to rally around. The extreme nationalist, anti-semitic Right have always had Jews and Americans as enemies. The Left's enemies has always been the same as the extreme Right's, but for different reasons. It is the American and Israeli war against anti-Semitic, anti-American Islamic fundamentalists that has at last brought the Jackboots and the Sandals together, yet, still opposed on other issues.<br>
<br>
<br>
The Left now see the Palestinians as the Vietcong of the 2000's, and Yasser Arafat is their new Ho Chi Minh. In France, Palestinians, gay activists, skinheads and feminists marched to oppose Israel's actions in the West Bank. The &quot;Sandalistas&quot; in America automatically opposed their country's retaliation for the September attacks. <br>
<br>
<br>
